solutions.content:
Remove a node from a linked list is a perfect scene to use two level pointer, aka, pointer to pointer.
The solution is very straight forward, use a pointer(named `walker`) to traverse the list:
	1. If we meet the deleting node, modify(delete) the node by the `walker`
	2. if not, modify `walker` to go on traversing.
There is also a c++ version, may be helpful for understanding.
```
impl Solution {
    pub fn remove_elements(head: Option<Box<ListNode>>, val: i32) -> Option<Box<ListNode>> {
        let mut head = head;
        let mut walker = &mut head;
        while walker.is_some() {
            if walker.as_ref().unwrap().val == val {
                *walker = walker.take().unwrap().next;
            } else {
                walker = &mut walker.as_mut().unwrap().next;
            }
        }
        head
    }
}
```

C++ verison
```
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* removeElements(ListNode* head, int val) {
        auto walker = &head;
        while (nullptr != *walker) {
            if (val == (*walker)->val) {
                auto to_delete = *walker;
                *walker = (*walker)->next;
                delete to_delete;
            } else {
                walker = &(*walker)->next;
            }
        }
        return head;
    }
};
```

